# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: metaflow
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Metaflow is a human-centric framework designed to help scientists and engineers **build and manage real-life AI and ML systems**.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Serving teams of all sizes and scale, Metaflow streamlines the entire development lifecycle—from rapid prototyping in notebooks to reliable, maintainable production deployments—enabling teams to iterate quickly and deliver robust systems efficiently.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Originally developed at Netflix and now supported by Outerbounds, Metaflow is designed to boost the productivity for research and engineering teams working on a wide variety of projects, from classical statistics to state-of-the-art deep learning and foundation models.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] By unifying code, data, and compute at every stage, Metaflow ensures seamless, end-to-end management of real-world AI and ML systems.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Today, Metaflow powers thousands of AI and ML experiences across a diverse array of companies, large and small, including Amazon, Doordash, Dyson, Goldman Sachs, Ramp, and many others.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Effortlessly scale horizontally and vertically in your cloud, utilizing both CPUs and GPUs, with fast data access for running massive embarrassingly parallel as well as gang-scheduled compute workloads reliably and efficiently.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Easily manage dependencies and deploy with one-click to highly available production orchestrators with built in support for reactive orchestration.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] For full documentation, check out our API Reference or see our Release Notes for the latest features and improvements.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] If you don't know where to start, Metaflow sandbox will have you running and exploring in seconds.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Once installed, a great way to get started is by following our tutorial.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] It walks you through creating and running your first Metaflow flow step by step.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] If you need help, don’t hesitate to reach out on our Slack community!
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] While you can get started with Metaflow easily on your laptop, the main benefits of Metaflow lie in its ability to scale out to external compute clusters and to deploy to production-grade workflow orchestrators.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] To benefit from these features, follow this guide to configure Metaflow and the infrastructure behind it appropriately.
[src:metaflow/blob-readme-md] Please see our contribution guide for more details.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science plays a critical role in modern decision-making by enabling organizations to extract actionable insights from large and complex datasets.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science also integrates domain knowledge from the underlying application domain (e.g., natural sciences, information technology, and medicine).
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science is multifaceted and can be described as a science, a research paradigm, a research method, a discipline, a workflow, and a profession.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science is "a concept to unify statistics, data analysis, informatics, and their related methods" to "understand and analyze actual phenomena" with data.
[src:metaflow/data-science] It uses techniques and theories drawn from many fields within the context of mathematics, statistics, computer science, information science, and domain knowledge.
[src:metaflow/data-science] However, data science is distinct from computer science and information science.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Turing Award winner Jim Gray imagined data science as a "fourth paradigm" of science (empirical, theoretical, computational, and now data-driven) and asserted that "everything about science is changing because of the impact of information technology" and the data deluge.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science is often described as a multidisciplinary and rapidly evolving field because it draws on techniques from diverse areas, such as computer science, statistics, information science, and other subject-specific disciplines.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Some researchers argue that the combination of the different fields resembles how information science was decades ago.
[src:metaflow/data-science] These similarities help clarify how data science gradually became its own field of study.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science is an interdisciplinary field focused on extracting knowledge from typically large data sets and applying the knowledge from that data to solve problems in other application domains.
[src:metaflow/data-science] The field encompasses preparing data for analysis, formulating data science problems, analyzing data, and summarizing these findings.
[src:metaflow/data-science] As such, it incorporates skills from computer science, mathematics, data visualization, graphic design, communication, and business.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Vasant Dhar writes that statistics emphasizes quantitative data and description.
[src:metaflow/data-science] In contrast, data science deals with quantitative and qualitative data (e.g., from images, text, sensors, transactions, customer information, etc.) and emphasizes prediction and action.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Andrew Gelman of Columbia University has described statistics as a non-essential part of data science.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Stanford professor David Donoho writes that data science is not distinguished from statistics by the size of datasets or use of computing and that many graduate programs misleadingly advertise their analytics and statistics training as the essence of a data-science program.
[src:metaflow/data-science] He describes data science as an applied field growing out of traditional statistics.
[src:metaflow/data-science] In 1962, John Tukey described a field he called "data analysis", which resembles modern data science.
[src:metaflow/data-science] In 1985, in a lecture given to the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing, C.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Jeff Wu used the term "data science" for the first time as an alternative name for statistics.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Later, attendees at a 1992 statistics symposium at the University of Montpellier II acknowledged the emergence of a new discipline focused on data of various origins and forms, combining established concepts and principles of statistics and data analysis with computing.
[src:metaflow/data-science] The term "data science" has been traced back to 1974, when Peter Naur proposed it as an alternative name to computer science.
[src:metaflow/data-science] However, the definition was still in flux.
[src:metaflow/data-science] After the 1985 lecture at the Chinese Academy of Sciences in Beijing, in 1997 C.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Jeff Wu again suggested that statistics should be renamed data science.
[src:metaflow/data-science] He reasoned that a new name would help statistics shed inaccurate stereotypes, such as being synonymous with accounting or limited to describing data.
[src:metaflow/data-science] In 1998, Hayashi Chikio argued for data science as a new, interdisciplinary concept, with three aspects: data design, collection, and analysis.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Davenport and DJ Patil declared "Data Scientist: The Sexiest Job of the 21st Century", a catchphrase that was picked up even by major-city newspapers like the *New York Times* and the *Boston Globe*.
[src:metaflow/data-science] A decade later, they reaffirmed it, stating that "the job is more in demand than ever with employers".
[src:metaflow/data-science] The modern conception of data science as an independent discipline is sometimes attributed to William S.
[src:metaflow/data-science] In 2014, the American Statistical Association's Section on Statistical Learning and Data Mining changed its name to the Section on Statistical Learning and Data Science, reflecting the ascendant popularity of data science.
[src:metaflow/data-science] The professional title of "data scientist" has been attributed to DJ Patil and Jeff Hammerbacher in 2008.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Though it was used by the National Science Board in their 2005 report "Long-Lived Digital Data Collections: Enabling Research and Education in the 21st Century", it referred broadly to any key role in managing a digital data collection.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data analysis typically involves working with structured datasets to answer specific questions or solve specific problems.
[src:metaflow/data-science] This can involve tasks such as data cleaning and data visualization to summarize data and develop hypotheses about relationships between variables.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data analysts typically use statistical methods to test these hypotheses and draw conclusions from the data.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science involves working with larger datasets that often require advanced computational and statistical methods to analyze.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data scientists often work with unstructured data such as text or images and use machine learning algorithms to build predictive models.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science often uses statistical analysis, data preprocessing, and supervised learning.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Cloud computing can offer access to large amounts of computational power and storage.
[src:metaflow/data-science] In big data, where volumes of information are continually generated and processed, these platforms can be used to handle complex and resource-intensive analytical tasks.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Some distributed computing frameworks are designed to handle big data workloads.
[src:metaflow/data-science] These frameworks can enable data scientists to process and analyze large datasets in parallel, which can reduce processing times.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Data science involves collecting, processing, and analyzing data which often includes personal and sensitive information.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Ethical concerns include potential privacy violations, bias perpetuation, and negative societal impacts.
[src:metaflow/data-science] Machine learning models can amplify existing biases present in training data, leading to discriminatory or unfair outcomes.
[src:metaflow/docs-metaflow-org] Metaflow makes it easy to build and manage real-life data science, AI, and ML projects.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:metaflow/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Launched in 2007, nearly a decade after Netflix, Inc. began its pioneering DVD-by-mail movie rental service, Netflix is the most-subscribed video on demand streaming media service, with 325 million paid memberships in more than 190 countries as of 2026.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] By 2022, "Netflix Original" productions accounted for half of its library in the United States and the namesake company had ventured into other categories, such as video game publishing of mobile games through its flagship service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] As of 2025, Netflix is the 18th most-visited website in the world, with 21.18% of its traffic coming from the US, followed by the United Kingdom at 6.01%, Canada at 4.94%, and Brazil at 4.24%.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix was founded by Marc Randolph and Reed Hastings as a DVD rental service on August 29, 1997, in Scotts Valley, California.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Launched on April 14, 1998, Netflix offered a per-rental model for each DVD but introduced a monthly subscription concept in September 1999, after which the per-rental model was dropped by early 2000.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In 2005, 35,000 different films were available, and Netflix shipped 1 million DVDs out every day.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Through its Red Envelope Entertainment division, Netflix licensed and distributed independent films such as *Born into Brothels* (2004) and *Sherrybaby* (2006).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In late 2006, Red Envelope Entertainment also expanded into producing original content with filmmakers such as John Waters.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix closed Red Envelope Entertainment in 2008.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Hastings reportedly told Mynette Louie in the late-1990s that his goal was always streaming media, and that Netflix rented DVDs only to grow its customer base for streaming.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] By the mid-2000s, data speeds and bandwidth costs improved sufficiently, allowing customers to download movies from the internet.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The original idea was a "Netflix box" that could download movies overnight and be ready to watch the next day.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] By 2005, Netflix had acquired movie rights and designed the box and service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] But after witnessing how popular streaming services such as YouTube were despite the lack of high-definition content, the concept of using a hardware device was scrapped and replaced with a streaming concept.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2007, the company launched a streaming media service, introducing video on demand via the Internet.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] However, at that time, it only had 1,000 films available for streaming, compared to 70,000 available on DVD.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The service, then called "Watch Now", at first required Internet Explorer on a computer.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Hollywood studios (including 20th Century Fox, Sony Pictures, MGM, Paramount Pictures, Universal Pictures, Warner Bros., New Line Cinema, and Lionsgate) licensed second-run content to the service, not expecting it to threaten their existing lucrative relationships with cable television.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2007, Netflix delivered its billionth DVD, a copy of *Babel* (2006) to a customer in Texas.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2007, Netflix recruited ReplayTV founder Anthony Wood, to build a "Netflix Player" that would allow streaming content to be played directly on a television rather than a desktop or laptop.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Hastings eventually shut down the project to help encourage other hardware manufacturers to include built-in Netflix support, which would be spun off as the digital media player product Roku.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2008, all rental-disc subscribers became entitled to unlimited streaming at no additional cost.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] This change came in response to the introduction of Hulu and to Apple's new video-rental services.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In August 2008, the Netflix database was corrupted and the company was unable to ship DVDs to customers for three days, leading the company to move all its data to the Amazon Web Services cloud.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2008, Netflix began offering subscribers rentals on Blu-ray and discontinued its sale of used DVDs.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In 2009, Netflix streams overtook its DVD shipments.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2010, Netflix agreed with Warner Bros. to delay new release rentals to 28 days after the DVDs became available for sale, in an attempt to help studios sell physical copies, and similar deals involving Universal Pictures and 20th Century Fox were reached on April 9.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2010, Netflix signed a deal to stream 300 indie movie titles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In July 2010, Netflix signed a deal to stream movies of Relativity Media.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] It also announced an expansion of its deal with Warner Bros.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Television adding more shows, including *Veronica Mars* and *Nip/Tuck*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In August 2010, Netflix reached a five-year deal worth nearly $1 billion to stream films from Paramount, Lionsgate, and Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The deal increased Netflix's annual spending fees, adding roughly $200 million per year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] It spent $117 million in the first six months of 2010 on streaming, up from $31 million in 2009.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2010, Netflix launched in Canada, its first international market.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2010, Netflix began offering a standalone streaming service separate from DVD rentals.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In 2010, Netflix acquired the rights to *Breaking Bad*, produced by Sony Pictures Television, after the show's third season, at a point where original broadcaster AMC had expressed the possibility of canceling the show.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Sony pushed Netflix to release *Breaking Bad* in time for the fourth season, which as a result, greatly expanded the show's audience on AMC due to new viewers binging on past episodes via Netflix, and doubling its viewership by the time of the fifth season.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] *Breaking Bad* is considered the first show to have this "Netflix effect".
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2011, Netflix announced agreements with several manufacturers to include branded Netflix buttons on the remote controls of devices compatible with the service, such as Blu-ray players.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] By May 2011, Netflix had become the largest source of Internet streaming traffic in North America, accounting for 30% of traffic during peak hours.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In July 2011, Netflix announced it would be separating its existing subscription plans into two: one covering the streaming and the other DVD rental services.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The cost for streaming would be $7.99 per month, while DVD rental would start at the same price.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2011, Netflix expanded to countries in Latin America.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] That same month, Netflix announced its intentions to rebrand and restructure its DVD home media rental service as an independent subsidiary called Qwikster, separating DVD rental and streaming services.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Customers reacted negatively, seeing this as a price increase and a betrayal of customer loyalty.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix's stock value dropped, and 800,000 of its 12 million customers cancelled their subscriptions.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix quickly apologized, and in October 2011, announced it would retain its DVD service under the name Netflix and that its streaming and DVD-rental plans would remain branded together.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] On September 26, 2011, Netflix announced a content deal with DreamWorks Animation.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2011, Netflix and The CW signed a multi-year output deal for its television shows.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2012, Netflix started its expansion to Europe, launching in the UK and Ireland.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2012, Netflix reached a multi-year agreement with The Weinstein Company.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March 2012, Netflix acquired the domain name DVD.com.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] By 2016, Netflix rebranded its DVD-by-mail service under the name *DVD.com, A Netflix Company*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2012, Netflix filed with the Federal Election Commission (FEC) to form a political action committee (PAC) called FLIXPAC.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix spokesperson Joris Evers tweeted that the intent was to "engage on issues like net neutrality, bandwidth caps, UBB and VPPA".
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In June 2012, Netflix signed a deal with Open Road Films.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In August 2012, Netflix and The Weinstein Company signed a multi-year output deal for RADiUS-TWC films.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2012, Epix signed a five-year streaming deal with Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] For the initial two years of this agreement, first-run and back-catalog content from Epix was exclusive to Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Epix films came to Netflix 90 days after premiering on Epix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] These included films from Paramount, Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer, and Lionsgate.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2012, Netflix launched in Denmark, Finland, Norway, and Sweden.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Direct-to-video releases were made available in 2013.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2013, Netflix signed an agreement with Time Warner's Turner Broadcasting System and Warner Bros.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Television to distribute Cartoon Network, Warner Bros.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Animation, and Adult Swim content, as well as TNT's *Dallas*, beginning in March 2013.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The rights to these programs were given to Netflix shortly after deals with Viacom to stream Nickelodeon and Nick Jr.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] For cost reasons, Netflix stated it would limit its expansion in 2013, adding only one new market—the Netherlands—in September of that year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] This expanded its availability to 40 territories.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix had long closely analyzed its customers' preferences.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Watch Now gave the company real-time data on their behavior, such as scenes that customers replayed or skipped, or when they stopped watching a show.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In 2011, Netflix began its efforts into original content development.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March, it made a straight-to-series order from MRC for the political drama *House of Cards*, led by Kevin Spacey, outbidding American cable networks.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] This marked the first instance of a first-run television series being specifically commissioned by the service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix executives said that its customers' love of films by Spacey and show director David Fincher caused the company to acquire the show.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Customers' tendency to binge watch many episodes without stopping caused it to release all 13 episodes of the show's first season at the same time.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November the same year, Netflix added two more significant productions to its roster: the comedy-drama *Orange Is the New Black* (*OITNB*), adapted from Piper Kerman's memoir, and a new season of the previously canceled Fox sitcom *Arrested Development*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix acquired the American rights to the Norwegian drama *Lilyhammer* after its television premiere on Norway's NRK1 in January 2012.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Notably departing from the traditional broadcast television model of weekly episode premieres, Netflix chose to release the entire first season on February 8 of the same year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March 2013, Netflix added a Facebook sharing feature, letting American subscribers access "Watched by your friends" and "Friends' Favorites" by agreeing.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] This was not legal until the Video Privacy Protection Act was modified in early 2013.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In August 2013, Netflix reintroduced the "Profiles" feature that permits accounts to house up to five user profiles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2013, Marvel Television and ABC Studios announced Netflix had ordered a slate of four television series based on the Marvel Comics characters Daredevil, Jessica Jones, Iron Fist, and Luke Cage.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Each of the four series received an initial order of 13 episodes, and Netflix also ordered a Defenders miniseries that would tie them together.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] *Daredevil* and *Jessica Jones* premiered in 2015.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The *Luke Cage* series premiered in September 2016, followed by *Iron Fist* in March 2017, and *The Defenders* in August 2017.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Marvel owner Disney later entered into other content agreements with Netflix, including acquiring its animated *Star Wars* series *Star Wars: The Clone Wars*, and a new sixth season.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2014, Netflix began to enter into agreements with American internet service providers, beginning with Comcast (whose customers had repeatedly complained of frequent buffering when streaming Netflix), to provide the service a direct connection to their networks.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2014, Netflix signed *Arrested Development* creator Mitchell Hurwitz and his production firm The Hurwitz Company to a multi-year deal to create original projects for the service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In May 2014, Netflix and Sony Pictures Animation had a major multi-deal to acquire streaming rights to produce films.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] It also began to introduce an updated logo, with a flatter appearance and updated typography.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2014, Netflix expanded into six new European markets, including Austria, Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, and Switzerland.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] On September 10, 2014, Netflix participated in Internet Slowdown Day by deliberately slowing down its speed in support of net neutrality regulations in the US.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2014, Netflix announced a four-film deal with Adam Sandler and his Happy Madison Productions.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2015, following the launch of *Daredevil*, Netflix director of content operations Tracy Wright announced that Netflix had added support for audio description, and had begun to work with its partners to add descriptions to its other original series over time.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The following year, as part of a settlement with the American Council of the Blind, Netflix agreed to provide descriptions for its original series within 30 days of their premiere, and add screen reader support and the ability to browse content by availability of descriptions.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March 2015, Netflix expanded to Australia and New Zealand.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2015, Netflix launched in Japan, its first country in Asia.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2015, Netflix launched in Italy, Portugal, and Spain.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2016, at the Consumer Electronics Show, Netflix announced a major international expansion of its service into 130 additional countries, making it available worldwide except in China, Syria, North Korea, Kosovo, and Crimea.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] As part of this expansion, Netflix officially launched its services in Africa, with a focus on South Africa, Kenya, and Nigeria.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Between 2018 and 2020, Netflix had started making significant investments in African storytelling, and hired Dorothy Ghettuba, a Kenyan media entrepreneur, as head of African Originals.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] According to the company, it has invested the equivalent of €160 million in film content production in Africa since it began working on the continent in 2016, with over 12,000 jobs created across Nigeria, Kenya, and South Africa.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2016, Hastings stated that the company planned to expand its in-house, Los Angeles-based Netflix Studios to grow its output; Hastings ruled out any potential acquisitions of existing studios.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In May 2016, Netflix created a tool called Fast.com to determine the speed of an Internet connection.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] It received praise for being "simple" and "easy to use", and does not include online advertising, unlike competitors.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2016, Netflix launched an offline playback feature, allowing users of the Netflix mobile apps on Android or iOS to cache content on their devices in standard or high quality for viewing offline, without an Internet connection.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix released an estimated 30 original series or films over that year, more than any network or cable channel.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2017, Netflix signed a music publishing deal with BMG Rights Management, whereby BMG would oversee rights outside of the US for music associated with Netflix Original content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix continues to handle these tasks in-house in the US.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2017, Netflix signed a licensing deal with IQIYI, a Chinese video streaming platform owned by Baidu, to allow selected Netflix Original content to be distributed in China on the platform.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In August 2017, Netflix acquired Millarworld, the creator-owned publishing company of comic book writer Mark Millar.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The purchase marked the first corporate acquisition to have been made by Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] That same month, Netflix entered into an exclusive development deal with Shonda Rhimes and her production company Shondaland.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2017, Netflix announced it would offer its low-broadband mobile technology to airlines to provide better in-flight Wi-Fi so passengers could watch movies on Netflix while on planes.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] That same month, Minister of Heritage Mélanie Joly announced that Netflix had agreed to make a CA$500 million (US$400 million) investment over the next five years in producing content in Canada.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The company denied that the deal was intended to result in a tax break.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix realized this goal by December 2018.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2017, Netflix iterated a goal of having half of its library consist of original content by 2019, announcing a plan to invest $8 billion on original content in 2018.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2017, Netflix introduced the "Skip Intro" feature, which allows customers to skip the intros to shows on its platform through a variety of techniques including manual reviewing, audio tagging, and machine learning.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2017, Netflix signed an exclusive multi-year deal with *Orange Is the New Black* creator Jenji Kohan.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] That same month, Netflix withdrew from co-hosting a party at the 75th Golden Globe Awards with The Weinstein Company due to the Harvey Weinstein sexual abuse cases.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2017, Netflix announced it would be making its first original Colombian series, to be executive produced by Ciro Guerra.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In December 2017, Netflix signed *Stranger Things* director-producer Shawn Levy and his production company 21 Laps Entertainment to what sources say is a four-year deal.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In 2017, Netflix invested in distributing exclusive stand-up comedy specials from Dave Chappelle, Louis C.K., Chris Rock, Jim Gaffigan, Bill Burr, and Jerry Seinfeld.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2018, Netflix acquired the rights to *The Cloverfield Paradox* (2018) from Paramount Pictures for $50 million and launched it on February 4, 2018, shortly after airing its first trailer during Super Bowl LII.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Analysts believed that Netflix's purchase of the film helped to make the film instantly profitable for Paramount compared to a more traditional theatrical release, while Netflix benefited from the surprise reveal.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March, the service ordered *Formula 1: Drive to Survive*, a racing docuseries following teams in the Formula One world championship.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March 2018, Sky UK announced an agreement with Netflix to integrate Netflix's subscription VOD offering into its pay-TV service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Customers with its high-end Sky Q set-top box and service will be able to see Netflix titles alongside their regular Sky channels.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In October 2022, Netflix revealed that its annual revenue from the UK subscribers in 2021 was £1.4bn.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2018, Netflix pulled out of the Cannes Film Festival, in response to new rules requiring competition films to have been released in French theaters.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The Cannes premiere of *Okja* in 2017 was controversial, and led to discussions over the appropriateness of films with simultaneous digital releases being screened at an event showcasing theatrical film; audience members also booed the Netflix production logo at the screening.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Netflix's attempts to negotiate to allow a limited release in France were curtailed by organizers, as well as French cultural exception law—where theatrically screened films are legally forbidden from being made available via video-on-demand services until at least 36 months after their release.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Besides traditional Hollywood markets as well as from partners like the BBC, Sarandos said the company was also looking to expand investments in non-traditional foreign markets due to the growth of viewers outside of North America.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] At the time, this included programs such as *Dark* from Germany, *Ingobernable* from Mexico, and *3%* from Brazil.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In May 2018, former president, Barack Obama, and his wife, Michelle Obama, signed a deal to produce docuseries, documentaries, and features for Netflix under the Obamas' newly formed production company, Higher Ground Productions.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In June 2018, Netflix announced a partnership with Telltale Games to port its adventure games to the service in a streaming video format, allowing simple controls through a television remote.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The first game, *Minecraft: Story Mode*, was released in November 2018.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In July 2018, Netflix earned the most Emmy nominations of any network for the first time with 112 nods.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In August 2018, the company signed a five-year exclusive overall deal with international best-selling author Harlan Coben.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] At the same time, the company signed an overall deal with *Gravity Falls* creator Alex Hirsch.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2018, Paramount Pictures signed a multi-picture film deal with Netflix, making Paramount the first major film studio to do so.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] A sequel to AwesomenessTV's *To All the Boys I've Loved Before* (2018) was released on Netflix under the title *To All the Boys: P.S.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] I Still Love You* (2020) as part of the agreement.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In December 2018, the company announced a partnership with ESPN Films on a television documentary chronicling Michael Jordan and the 1997–98 Chicago Bulls season titled *The Last Dance*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] It was released internationally on Netflix and became available for streaming in the US three months after a broadcast airing on ESPN.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2019, *Sex Education* made its debut as a Netflix Original series, receiving much critical acclaim.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] On January 22, 2019, Netflix sought and was approved for membership into the Motion Picture Association of America (MPAA), making it the first streaming service to join the association.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2019, *The Haunting* creator Mike Flanagan joined frequent collaborator Trevor Macy as a partner in Intrepid Pictures, and the duo signed an exclusive deal with Netflix to produce television content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In May 2019, Netflix contracted with Dark Horse Entertainment to make television series and films based on comics from Dark Horse Comics.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In July 2019, Netflix announced it would be opening a hub at Shepperton Studios as part of a deal with Pinewood Group.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In early-August 2019, Netflix negotiated an exclusive multi-year film and television deal with *Game of Thrones* creators and showrunners David Benioff and D.B.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The first Netflix production created by Benioff and Weiss was planned as an adaptation of Liu Cixin's science fiction novel *The Three-Body Problem*, part of the *Remembrance of Earth's Past* trilogy.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In September 2019, in addition to renewing *Stranger Things* for a fourth season, Netflix signed The Duffer Brothers to an overall deal covering future film and television projects for the service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In November 2019, Netflix and Nickelodeon entered into a multi-year agreement to produce several original animated feature films and television series based on Nickelodeon's library of characters.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] This agreement expanded on their existing relationship, in which new specials based on the past Nickelodeon series *Invader Zim* and *Rocko's Modern Life* (*Invader Zim: Enter the Florpus* and *Rocko's Modern Life: Static Cling,* respectively) were released by Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Other new projects planned under the team-up include a music project featuring Squidward Tentacles from the animated television series *SpongeBob SquarePants*, and films based on *The Loud House* and *Rise of the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The agreement with Disney ended in 2019 due to the launch of Disney+, with its Marvel productions moving exclusively to the service in 2022.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] Also in November 2019, Netflix announced it had signed a long-term lease to save the Paris Theatre, the last single-screen movie theater in Manhattan.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] The company oversaw several renovations at the theater, including new seats and a concession stand.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In January 2020, Netflix announced a new four-film deal with Adam Sandler worth up to $275 million.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In February 2020, Netflix formed partnerships with six Japanese creators to produce an original Japanese anime project.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] This partnership includes manga creator group CLAMP, manga creator Shin Kibayashi, manga creator Yasuo Ohtagaki, novelist and film director Otsuichi, novelist Tow Ubukata, and manga creator Mari Yamazaki.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In March 2020, ViacomCBS announced it will be producing two spin-off films based on *SpongeBob SquarePants* for Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In April 2020, Peter Chernin's Chernin Entertainment made a multi-year first-look deal with Netflix to make films.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In May 2020, Netflix announced the acquisition of Grauman's Egyptian Theatre from the American Cinematheque to use as a special events venue.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] In July 2020, Netflix appointed Sarandos as co-CEO.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p01] That same month, Netflix invested in *Black Mirror* creators Charlie Brooker and Annabel Jones' new production outfit Broke And Bones.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In September 2020, Netflix signed a multi-million dollar deal with the Duke and Duchess of Sussex.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Harry and Meghan agreed to a multi-year deal promising to create TV shows, films, and children's content as part of their commitment to stepping away from the duties of the royal family.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] That same month, Hastings released a book about Netflix culture titled *No Rules Rules: Netflix and the Culture of Reinvention*, which was coauthored by Erin Meyer.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In December 2020, Netflix signed a first-look deal with Millie Bobby Brown to develop and star in several projects, including a potential action franchise.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In March 2021, Netflix earned the most Academy Award nominations of any studio, with 36 nods.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix won seven Academy Awards, which was the most by any studio.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Later that year, Netflix also won more Emmys than any other network or studio with 44 wins, tying the record for most Emmys won in a single year set by CBS in 1974.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2021, Sony Pictures Entertainment announced an agreement for Netflix to hold the US pay television window rights to its releases beginning in 2022, replacing Starz and expanding upon an existing agreement with Sony Pictures Animation.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The agreement also includes a first-look deal for any future direct-to-streaming films being produced by Sony Pictures, with Netflix required to commit to a minimum number of them.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On April 27, Netflix announced it was opening its first Canadian headquarters in Toronto.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company also announced that it would open an office in Sweden, Rome, and Istanbul to increase its original content in those regions.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In early-June, Netflix hosted a first-ever week-long virtual event called "Geeked Week", where it shared exclusive news, new trailers, cast appearances, and more about upcoming genre titles like *The Witcher*, *The Cuphead Show!*, and *The Sandman*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On June 7, Jennifer Lopez's Nuyorican Productions signed a multi-year first-look deal with Netflix spanning feature films, TV series, and unscripted content, with an emphasis on projects that support diverse female actors, writers, and filmmakers.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On June 10, Netflix announced it was launching an online store for curated products tied to the Netflix brand and shows such as *Stranger Things* and *The Witcher*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On June 21, Steven Spielberg's Amblin Partners signed a deal with Netflix to release multiple new feature films for the streaming service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On June 30, Powerhouse Animation Studios (the studio behind Netflix's *Castlevania*) announced signing a first-look deal with the streamer to produce more animated series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In July 2021, Netflix hired Mike Verdu, a former executive from Electronic Arts and Facebook, as vice president of game development, along with plans to add video games by 2022.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix announced plans to release mobile games that would be included in subscribers' service plans.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Trial offerings were first launched for Netflix users in Poland in August 2021, offering premium mobile games based on *Stranger Things,* including *Stranger Things 3: The Game*, for free to subscribers through the Netflix mobile app.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On July 14, 2021, Netflix signed a first-look deal with Joey King, star of *The Kissing Booth* franchise, in which King would produce and develop films for Netflix via her All The King's Horses production company.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On July 21, Zack Snyder, director of Netflix's *Army of the Dead*, announced he had signed his production company The Stone Quarry to a first-look deal with Netflix; his upcoming projects included a sequel to *Army of the Dead* and a sci-fi adventure film titled *Rebel Moon*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In 2019, he had agreed to produce an anime-style web series inspired by Norse mythology.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As of August 2021, Netflix Originals made up 40% of Netflix's overall library in the US.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company announced that "TUDUM: A Netflix Global Fan Event", a three-hour virtual behind the scenes featuring first-look reveals for 100 of the streamer's series, films, and specials, would have its inaugural show in late September 2021.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] According to Netflix, the show garnered 25.7 million views across Netflix's 29 Netflix YouTube channels, Twitter, Twitch, Facebook, TikTok, and Tudum.com.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Also in September, the company announced The Queen's Ball: A Bridgerton Experience, an immersive, Regency-era ball, launching in 2022 in Los Angeles, Chicago, Montreal, and Washington, D.C.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Then *Squid Game*, a South Korean survival drama created and produced by Hwang Dong-hyuk, rapidly became the service's most-watched show within a week of its launch in many markets on September 17, 2021, including Korea, the US, and the UK.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Within its first 28 days on the service, *Squid Game* drew more than 111 million viewers, surpassing *Bridgerton* and becoming Netflix's most-watched show.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On September 20, Netflix signed a long-term lease with Aviva Investors to operate and expand the Longcross Studios in Surrey, UK.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On September 21, Netflix announced it would acquire the Roald Dahl Story Company, which manages the rights to Roald Dahl's stories and characters, for an undisclosed price and would operate it as an independent company.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company acquired Night School Studio, an independent video game developer, on September 28.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On October 13, 2021, Netflix announced the launch of the Netflix Book Club, partnering with Starbucks for a social series called *But Have You Read the Book?*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Uzo Aduba became inaugural host of the series and announced monthly book selections set to be adapted by the streamer.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Aduba speaks with the cast, creators, and authors about the book adaptation process over a cup of coffee at Starbucks.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Through October 2021, Netflix commonly reported viewership for its programming based on the number of viewers or households that watched a show in a given period (such as the first 28 days from its premiere) for at least two minutes.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix officially launched mobile games on November 2, 2021, for Android users around the world.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Through the app, subscribers had free access to five games, including two previously made *Stranger Things* titles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix intends to add more games to this service over time.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On November 9, the collection launched for iOS.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Some games in the collection require an active internet connection to play, while others will be available offline.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix Kids' accounts will not have games available.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On November 16, Netflix announced the launch of "Top10 on Netflix.com", a new website with weekly global and country lists of the most popular titles on its service based on its new viewership metrics.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On November 22, Netflix announced that it would acquire Scanline VFX, the visual effects and animation company behind *Cowboy Bebop* and *Stranger Things*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On the same day, Roberto Patino signed a deal with Netflix and established his production banner, Analog Inc., in partnership with the company.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Patino's first project under the deal is a series adaptation of Image Comics' *Nocterra*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 6, 2021, Netflix and Stage 32 announced that they have teamed up the workshops at the Creating Content for the Global Marketplace program.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 7, 2021, Netflix partnered with IllumiNative, a woman-led non-profit organization, for the Indigenous Producers Training Program.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 9, Netflix announced the launch of "Tudum", an official companion website that offers news, exclusive interviews and behind-the-scenes videos for its original television shows and films.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 13, Netflix signed a multi-year overall deal with Kalinda Vazquez.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 16, Netflix signed a multi-year creative partnership with Spike Lee and his production company 40 Acres and a Mule Filmworks to develop film and television projects.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In compliance with the EU Audiovisual Media Services Directive and its implementation in France, Netflix reached commitments with French broadcasting authorities and film guilds, as required by law, to invest a specific amount of its annual revenue into original French films and series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] These films must be theatrically released and would not be allowed to be carried on Netflix until 15 months after their release.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In January 2022, Netflix ordered additional sports docuseries from *Drive to Survive* producers Box to Box Films, including a series that would follow PGA Tour golfers (*Full Swing*), and another that would follow professional tennis players (*Break Point*).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company announced plans to acquire Next Games in March 2022 for €65 million as part of Netflix's expansions into gaming.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Next Games had developed the mobile title *Stranger Things: Puzzle Tales* as well as two *The Walking Dead* mobile games.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Later that month, Netflix also acquired the Texas-based mobile game developer, Boss Fight Entertainment, for an undisclosed sum.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In March 2022, Netflix announced a partnership with Dr.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Seuss Enterprises to produce five new series and specials based on Seuss properties following the success of *Green Eggs and Ham*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On March 29, Netflix announced it would open an office in Poland to serve as a hub for its original productions across Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On March 30, Netflix extended its lease agreement with Martini Film Studios, just outside Vancouver, Canada, for another five years.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Following the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Netflix suspended its operations and future projects in Russia.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It also announced that it would not comply with a proposed directive by Roskomnadzor requiring all internet streaming services with more than 100,000 subscribers to integrate the major free-to-air channels (which are primarily state-owned).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] A month later, ex-Russian subscribers filed a class action lawsuit against Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2022, Netflix stated that 100 million households globally were sharing passwords to their account with others, and that Canada and the US accounted for 30 million of them.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Following these announcements, Netflix's stock price fell by 35%.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] By June 2022, Netflix had laid off 450 full-time and contract employees as part of the company's plan to trim costs amid lower than expected subscriber growth.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On April 13, 2022, Netflix released the series *Our Great National Parks*, which was hosted and narrated by former US President Barack Obama.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It also partnered with Group Effort Initiative, a company founded by Ryan Reynolds and Blake Lively, to provide opportunities behind the camera for those in underrepresented communities.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On the same day, Netflix partnered with Lebanon-based Arab Fund For Arts And Culture for supporting the Arab female filmmakers.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It would provide a one-time grant of $250,000 to female producers and directors in the Arab world through the company's Fund for Creative Equity.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Also on the same day, Netflix announced an *Exploding Kittens* mobile card game tied to a new animated TV series, which would launch in May.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix formed a creative partnership with J.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company also formed a partnership with Japan's Studio Colorido, signing a multi-film deal to boost its anime content in Asia.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The streaming giant is said to co-produce three feature films with the studio, the first of which would premiere in September 2022.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On April 28, the company launched its inaugural Netflix Is a Joke comedy festival, featuring more than 250 shows over 12 nights at 30-plus locations across Los Angeles, including the first-ever stand-up show at Dodger Stadium.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The first volume of *Stranger Things 4* logged Netflix's biggest premiere weekend ever for an original series with 286.79 million hours viewed.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] This was preceded by a new *Stranger Things* interactive experience hosted in New York City that was developed by the show's creators.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] After the release of the second volume of *Stranger Things 4* on July 1, 2022, it became Netflix's second title to receive more than one billion hours viewed.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On July 19, 2022, Netflix announced plans to acquire Australian animation studio Animal Logic.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Also that month, in collaboration with Sennheiser, Netflix began to add Ambeo 2-channel audio mixes (referred to as "spatial audio") to selected original productions, which allows simulated surround sound on stereo speakers and headphones.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In September 2022, Netflix opened an office in Warsaw, Poland, responsible for the service's operations in 28 markets in Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In October 2022, Netflix signed a creative partnership with Andrea Berloff and John Gatins.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On October 11, Netflix signed up with the Broadcasters' Audience Research Board for external measurement of viewership in the UK.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On October 12, Netflix signed to build a production complex at Fort Monmouth in Eatontown, New Jersey.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On October 18, Netflix began exploring a cloud gaming offering and opened a new gaming studio in Southern California.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November 2022, Netflix announced a strategic partnership with The Seven, a Japanese production company owned by TBS Holdings, to produce multiple original live-action titles over the next five years.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In December 2022, Netflix announced that 60% of its subscribers had watched a Korean drama.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] CEO Ted Sarandos attributed the increase in viewership of Korean content among Americans to Korean films and dramas being "often unpredictable" and catching "the American audience by surprise".
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Inn January 2023, Netflix announced plans to open an engineering hub in its Warsaw office to provide Netflix's creative partners with software solutions for the production of films and series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In February 2023, Netflix launched a wider rollout of spatial audio, and began allowing Premium subscribers to download content for offline playback on up to six devices (expanded from four).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In March 2023, Netflix broadcast its first-ever global live-streaming event, the stand-up comedy special *Chris Rock: Selective Outrage*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix reworked its viewership metrics again in June 2023.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Viewership of shows was measured during the first 91 days of availability, instead of the first 28 days, and are now based on the total viewership hours divided by the total hours of the show itself.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] This provided more equal considerations for shorter shows and movies compared to longer ones.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In August 2023, the company announced Netflix Stories, a collection of interactive narrative games from Netflix series and movies such as *Love is Blind*, *Money Heist,* and *Virgin River*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In January 2023, Hastings stepped down from his role as co-CEO and assumed the role of executive chairman.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] He was replaced by Greg Peters, who joined Ted Sarandos as co-CEOs of Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Peters previously served as Chief Operating Officer (COO) and Chief Product Officer (CPO), while Sarandos served as Chief Content Officer (CCO).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2023, Netflix announced it would discontinue its DVD-by-mail service on September 29.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Users of the service were able to keep the DVDs they had received.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Over its lifetime, the service had sent out over 5 billion shipments.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In October 2023, Eunice Kim was promoted to CPO and Elizabeth Stone was promoted to Chief Technology Officer (CTO).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] That same month, amid a restructuring of its animation division, Netflix announced a multi-film agreement with Skydance Animation beginning with *Spellbound* (2024).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The agreement partially replaces one it had with Apple TV+.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In December 2023, Netflix released its first "What We Watched: A Netflix Engagement Report", a look at viewership for every original and licensed title watched more than 50,000 hours from January to June 2023.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company also announced plans to publish the report twice a year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In its first report for the first six months of 2023, it revealed that *The Night Agent* was the most watched show globally during that period.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As part of the agreement, Netflix also acquired the international rights to WWE's main weekly programs (*Raw*, *SmackDown*, and *NXT*) and pay-per-view events outside of the US, and the former WWE Network library of supplemental and archive content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The agreement was reported to be valued at $500 million per-year over ten years.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix would later acquire the library rights in the US under a separate deal, replacing an agreement with Peacock.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In February 2024, Netflix joined with Peter Morgan, creator of Netflix series *The Crown*, to produce the play *Patriots* on Broadway.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The venture is the first Broadway credit for the company but not its first stage project.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It was actively involved as a producer of *Stranger Things: The First Shadow* in London.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Both productions share a lead producer, Sonia Friedman.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In May 2024, the company hosted its second Netflix Is a Joke festival in Los Angeles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It streamed several specials from the festival live, including Katt Williams's *Woke Folk* and *The Roast of Tom Brady*, both of which ranked on Netflix's global top 10 the following two weeks.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] That same month, Netflix announced it would stream both National Football League Christmas games in 2024.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] For 2025 and 2026, the streamer would have exclusive rights to at least one NFL Christmas game each year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In June 2024, Netflix announced it would develop new entertainment venues known as "Netflix House" at the King of Prussia Mall in Pennsylvania and Galleria Dallas in Texas.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The spaces would feature retail shops, restaurants, and other interactive experiences related to Netflix Original content, building upon other "pop-up" initiatives to promote individual programs.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix House Philadelphia would feature immersive experiences for *Wednesday* and *One Piece*, while Netflix House Dallas will feature *Stranger Things: Escape the Dark* and *Squid Game: Survive the Trials*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix House Las Vegas Strip will open in 2027.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November 2024, Netflix announced it would discontinue further work on interactive specials and remove all but four of them from the platform, citing a desire to focus on "technological efforts in other areas".
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On November 15, Netflix streamed a boxing event from AT&T Stadium in Arlington, Texas, featuring as co-main events an exhibition match between Jake Paul and Mike Tyson, and Katie Taylor versus Amanda Serrano for the WBA, WBC, IBF, WBO, and *The Ring* lightweight titles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix stated that the event had an "average minute audience" (AMA) of 108 million worldwide, and that the AMA of 47 million in the US made the Taylor versus Serrano bout the most-watched women's professional sporting event in US history.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In December 2024, FIFA announced that Netflix would be the exclusive American broadcaster of the 2027 and 2031 FIFA Women's World Cup, in what was deemed the platform's most significant push into sports content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 25, Netflix aired its first-ever NFL games: the Kansas City Chiefs versus the Pittsburgh Steelers, and the Baltimore Ravens versus the Houston Texans.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The games both averaged over 30 million global viewers and became the two most-streamed NFL games in American history, while simultaneously creating Netflix's most-watched Christmas Day ever in the US.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In January 2025, Netflix announced it had exceeded 300 million subscribers worldwide after adding a record 18.9 million in Q4 of 2024, amounting to 41 million for the full year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In May 2025, Netflix announced a redesign of its home screen for the first time since 2013, which has a simplified appearance with more prominent metadata, and replaces the sidebar menu with a streamlined section of tabs along the top of the screen.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix stated that the redesign was meant to allow users to "have an easier time figuring out if a title is right for them", and be more reflective of new types of content offerings such as sports and other live events.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In August 2025, Netflix announced an exclusivity deal to stream the World Baseball Classic in Japan starting in 2026.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The 2026 edition marks the first time it will stream a live event in Japan.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Through this agreement, Netflix will stream all 47 games of the 2026 World Baseball Classic live and on-demand for its users in Japan.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The animated musical *KPop Demon Hunters* (2025) became Netflix's most popular film of all time later that month.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November 2025, Netflix acquired rights to selected Major League Baseball (MLB) events for the 2026, 2027, and 2028 seasons in the United States, including a primetime Opening Night game, the Home Run Derby during the MLB All-Star Game, and the MLB at Field of Dreams game.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 5, 2025, Netflix, Inc. initially won a bid to acquire Warner Bros.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Paramount Skydance subsequently made hostile, all-cash counter-offers for the entirety of WBD, assessing that its offer had fewer regulatory burdens and would be better for shareholders.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On February 26, 2026, WBD agreed to be acquired by Paramount Skydance for $31 per-share, valuing the company at $111 billion.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix subsequently backed out of bidding, considering its own offer to be "no longer financially attractive".
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Paramount Skydance would pay Netflix a $2.8 billion breakup fee.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In late-2025, Netflix began to make shifts into podcasts, acquiring rights to exclusively carry video from selected shows from iHeartMedia, Barstool Sports, (including *Pardon My Take*, *Spittin' Chiclets*, and *The Ryen Russillo* *Show*) and *The Ringer*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In 2026, Netflix began to premiere its own original podcasts, including *The Pete Davidson Show*, *The White House with Michael Irvin*, *Allegedly with Ellison Barber*, *Shut Up Evan* with Evan Ross Katz, *We're Back!
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] With Brian Williams*, *The Puzzle Room with David Kwong*, and *The Rotten Files with Stephanie Soo*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2026, Netflix introduced a new mobile design to make it easier to find something to watch.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] This new experience included "Clips," a vertical video feed featuring short clips from Netflix series, films and specials tailored to each member.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In the same month, the company announced Reed Hastings would step down from its board in June of that year.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In May 2026, the company released “The Netflix Effect," outlining the impact since the company expanded to more than 190 countries in 2016.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] This included contributing $325 billion to the global economy, investing $135 billion in the TV and film industry, and creating 425,000 jobs.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Also in May 2026, Netflix announced that the ads tier had reached 250 million monthly active viewers.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix is available in every country and territory except for China, Crimea, North Korea, Syria, and Russia.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In January 2016, Netflix announced it would begin VPN blocking since it can be used to watch videos from a country where they are unavailable.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The result of the VPN block is that people can only watch videos available worldwide and other videos are hidden from search results.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Hebrew and Arabic's right-to-left interface orientation, which is a common localization strategy in many markets, are what define the Middle Eastern user interface's localization, and in some regions, Netflix offers a more affordable mobile-only subscription.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Customers can subscribe to one of three plans; the difference in plans relates to video resolution, the number of simultaneous streams, and the number of devices to which content can be downloaded.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] At the end of Q1 2022, Netflix estimated that 100 million households globally were sharing passwords to their account with others.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In March 2022, Netflix began to charge a fee for additional users in Chile, Peru, and Costa Rica to attempt to control account sharing.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On July 18, 2022, Netflix announced that it would test the account sharing feature in more countries, including Argentina, Dominican Republic, El Salvador, Guatemala and Honduras.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On October 17, Netflix launched Profile Transfer to help end account sharing.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On July 13, 2022, Netflix announced plans to launch an advertising-supported subscription option.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix's planned advertising tier would not allow subscribers to download content like the existing ad-free platform.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On July 20, 2022, it was announced that the advertising-supported tier would be coming to Netflix in 2023 but it would not feature the full library of content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In October, the launch date was announced as November 3, 2022, and was launched in 12 countries: US, Canada, Mexico, Brazil, UK, France, Germany, Italy, Spain, Australia, Japan and South Korea.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The ad-supported plan was called "Basic with Ads" and it cost $6.99 per month in the US at launch.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On February 24, 2023, Netflix cut subscription prices in more than 30 countries around the world to attract more subscribers from those countries.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Malaysia, Indonesia, Thailand, the Philippines, Croatia, Venezuela, Kenya, and Iran are on the list of countries where the cost for a subscription will be reduced.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In the same month stronger anti-password-sharing rules were expanded to Canada, New Zealand, Portugal, and Spain.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In May 2023, these measures were further expanded to US and Brazil subscribers.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In July 2023, Netflix added 5.9 million subscribers for the second quarter of the year for a total of 238.39 million subscribers overall.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The US and Canada accounted for 1.2 million subscribers which was the largest regional quarterly gain since 2021.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In February, Netflix announced it would enforce stricter regulations on password sharing, and by May 2023 it began cracking down in the US, UK, and Australia.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Under these new rules, multiple people can use and share one account, but they have to be under the same household.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix defines a household as people who live in the same location as the owner of the account.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Users are asked to set a primary location based on the device's IP address.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix reported 8.05 million new subscribers in Q2 2024, up from 5.9 million subscribers added in Q2 2023.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In July 2024, Netflix started phasing out its cheapest subscription plan for users in France and the US, a year after the plan was removed for Canada and the UK.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Members in these countries have the option to sign up for either the standard ad-free plan or the ad plan.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2026, Netflix raised its U.S. subscription prices across all plans.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In May 2026, Netflix announced that the ad tier will expand to 15 new countries in 2027, including Austria, Belgium, Colombia, Denmark, Indonesia, Ireland, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway, Peru, the Philippines, Poland, Sweden, Switzerland and Thailand.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix can be accessed via a web browser, while Netflix apps are available on various platforms, including Blu-ray players, tablet computers, mobile phones, smart TVs, digital media players, and video game consoles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Several older devices no longer support Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] For home gaming consoles, this includes the PlayStation 2, PlayStation 3, PlayStation TV, Wii and Wii U.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] For handheld gaming consoles, this includes the Nintendo 3DS family of systems and the PlayStation Vita.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The second and third generation Apple TV previously supported Netflix with an ad-free plan, but the app was automatically removed on these devices on July 31, 2024.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The maximum video resolution supported on computers is dependent on the DRM systems available on a particular operating system and web browser.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] "Netflix Originals" are content that is produced, co-produced, or distributed exclusively by Netflix.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix funds its original shows differently than other TV networks when it signs a project, providing the money upfront and immediately ordering two seasons of most series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It keeps licensing rights, which normally give production companies future revenue opportunities from syndication, merchandising, etc.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Over the years, Netflix output ballooned to a level unmatched by any television network or streaming service.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] According to *Variety Insight*, Netflix produced a total of 240 new original shows and movies in 2018, then climbed to 371 in 2019, a figure "greater than the number of original series that the entire U.S.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] TV industry released in 2005." The Netflix budget allocated to production increased annually, reaching $13.6 billion in 2021 and projected to hit $18.9 billion by 2025, a figure that once again overshadowed any of its competitors.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As of August 2022, original productions made up 50% of Netflix's overall library in the US.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix has exclusive pay TV deals with several studios.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The deals give Netflix exclusive streaming rights while adhering to the structures of traditional pay TV terms.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Distributors that have licensed content to Netflix include Warner Bros., Universal Pictures, Sony Pictures Entertainment and previously The Walt Disney Studios.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix also holds current and back-catalog rights to television programs distributed by Walt Disney Television, DreamWorks Classics, Kino International, PBS, Warner Bros.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Formerly, the streaming service also held rights to select television programs distributed by NBCUniversal Television Distribution, Sony Pictures Television and 20th Century Fox Television.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix negotiated to distribute animated films from Universal that HBO declined to acquire, such as *The Lorax*, *ParaNorman*, and *Minions*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix holds exclusive streaming rights to the film library of Studio Ghibli (except *Grave of the Fireflies*) worldwide except in the US and Japan as part of an agreement signed with Ghibli's international sales holder Wild Bunch in 2020.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Trial offerings were first launched for Netflix users in Poland in August 2021, offering premium mobile games based on *Stranger Things* including *Stranger Things 3: The Game*, for free to subscribers through the Netflix mobile app.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Verdu said in October 2022 that besides continuing to expand its portfolio of games, it was also interested in cloud gaming options.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] To support the games effort, Netflix began acquiring and forming a number of studios.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company acquired Night School Studio, an independent video game developer, in September 2021.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix announced plans to acquire Next Games in March 2022 for €65 million as part of Netflix's expansions into gaming.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Later in the month, Netflix also acquired the Texas-based mobile game developer, Boss Fight Entertainment, for an undisclosed sum.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix opened a mobile game studio in Helsinki, Finland in September 2022, and a new studio, its fifth overall, in southern California in October 2022, alongside the acquisition of Spry Fox in Seattle.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In June 2024, Verdu was moved into a new role focusing on "innovation in game development." The next month, Netflix hired Alain Tascan, vice president of game development at Epic Games, to head up Netflix Games.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As of July 2024, Netflix has over 80 games in development, releasing at least one game each month to attract fans.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The company shut down its Southern California "Team Blue" AAA gaming studio in October 2024, leading to the departure of developers like *Overwatch* producer Chacko Sonny, *Halo* veteran Joseph Staten and *God of War* art director Rafael Grassetti.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix indicated that it maintains a commitment to grow its gaming business despite the changes.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In late October, Netflix announced several games based on hit series including Netflix Stories: Outer Banks, Netflix Stories: A Perfect Couple, Netflix Stories: A Virgin River Christmas, and The Ultimatum: Choices, as well as a new daily word game in partnership with TED Talks, TED Tumblewords.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On December 12, 2024, at The Game Awards 2024, Netflix Games revealed game designer Yu Suzuki's next game *Steel Paws*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November 2025, Netflix released its first batch of TV games which members play by using their phone as a controller.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The games included *Boggle Party*, *Lego Party*, *Pictionary: Game Night*, *Tetris Time Warp* and *Party Crasher: Fool Your Friends*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2026, Netflix launched "Netflix Playground", a gaming app for children featuring ad-free, offline-playable games based on popular characters, as part of its strategy to expand in family-oriented gaming.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix began with more focus on sports-related documentaries, like the popular *Drive To Survive* series, before moving toward live-action sports with one-off events.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] First was *The Netflix Cup* on November 14, 2023, featuring drivers and golfers from the docu-series *Formula 1: Drive to Survive* and *Full Swing.* Next came *The Netflix Slam* in March 2024, which showed an exhibition match between tennis stars Rafael Nadal and Carlos Alcaraz.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November 2024, Netflix streamed a boxing fight between former world heavyweight champion Mike Tyson and YouTuber Jake Paul.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] More than 60 million households watched the match.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] This marked the start of the company's broadcast of live boxing fights.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In December 2024, Netflix would become FIFA's exclusive US broadcaster of the 2027 and 2031 FIFA Women's World Cup.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix paid $5 billion to stream Raw, WWE’s flagship weekly wrestling show, for 10 years, starting in January 2025.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In the fall of 2025, Netflix moved into the field of baseball.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In August, Netflix announced an exclusivity deal to stream the World Baseball Classic in Japan starting in 2026.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November, it acquired rights to selected Major League Baseball (MLB) games for the 2026 to 2028 seasons.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In December 2025, Netflix broadcast its fourth major boxing event with the fight between Jake Paul and former world heavyweight champion Anthony Joshua, on December 19.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In March 2026, it was announced that Elle Duncan was leaving ESPN to become Netflix's first sports anchor.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Also that month, former baseball player Barry Bonds was announced to be joining Netflix for MLB coverage.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As of April 2026, Netflix was in the running, along with YouTube and Fox, for a five-game NFL package.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Bidders would have the ability to pick the five specific games, with options believed to include the Week 1 game in Australia, a Thanksgiving eve game (which is not official but apparently inevitable), a second Black Friday game, and a Christmas Eve game, among others.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix freely peers with Internet service providers (ISPs) directly and at common Internet exchange points.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In June 2012, a custom content delivery network, Open Connect, was announced.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] For larger ISPs with over 100,000 subscribers, Netflix offers free *Netflix Open Connect* computer appliances that cache its content within the ISPs' data centers or networks to further reduce Internet transit costs.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] By August 2016, Netflix closed its last physical data center, but continued to develop its Open Connect technology.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] A 2016 study at the University of London detected 233 individual Open Connect locations on over six continents, with the largest amount of traffic in the US, followed by Mexico.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As of July 2017, Netflix series and movies accounted for more than a third of all prime-time download Internet traffic in North America.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] On October 1, 2008, Netflix offered access to its service via a public application programming interface (API).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] It allowed access to data for all Netflix titles, and allows users to manage their movie queues.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The API was free and allowed commercial use.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In June 2012, Netflix began to restrict the availability of its public API.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix instead focused on a small number of known partners using private interfaces, since most traffic came from those private interfaces.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In November 2014, Netflix retired the public API.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix then partnered with the developers of eight services deemed the most valuable, including Instant Watcher, Fanhattan, Yidio and Nextguide.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix presents viewers with recommendations based on interactions with the service, such as previous viewing history and ratings of viewed content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] These are often grouped into genres and formats, or feature the platform's highest-rated content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Each title is presented with a thumbnail.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Before around 2015, these were the same key art for everyone, but since then has been customized.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix may select a specific key art for a thumbnail based on viewing history, such as an actor or scene type based on genre preferences.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Some thumbnails are generated from video stills.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The Netflix recommendation system is a vital part of the streaming platform's success, enabling personalized content suggestions for hundreds of millions of subscribers worldwide.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Using advanced machine learning algorithms, Netflix analyzes user interactions, including viewing history, searches, and ratings, to deliver personalized recommendations for movies and TV shows.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The recommendation system considers individual user preferences, similarities with other users with comparable tastes, specific title attributes (genre, release year, etc.), device usage patterns, and viewing time.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] As users interact with the platform and provide feedback with their viewing habits, the recommendation system is able to adapt and refine its suggestions over time.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix uses a two-tiered ranking system, using the presentation of titles on the homepage for easy navigation to maximize user engagement.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] This is done by organizing content into rows and ranking the titles within each row based on how much the user would be interested in it.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix also uses A/B testing to determine what causes the biggest interest and engagement related to options concerning movie suggestions and how titles are organized.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Tags like "bittersweet", "sitcom", or "intimate" are assigned to each title by Netflix employees.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix also uses the tags to create recommendation micro-genres like "Goofy TV Shows" or "Girls Night In".
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] Netflix launched "responsive recommendations", which display titles on the home page based on what its users are actively searching, in 2025.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] In April 2026, a team from Netflix and INSAIT published an inpainting model called VOID ("Video Object and Interaction Deletion"), a tool that removes objects from videos and changes further frames based on its understanding of physical causality.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p02] The model was based on another model from Alibaba PAI.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] On July 18, 2013, Netflix earned the first Primetime Emmy Awards nominations for original streaming programs at the 65th Primetime Emmy Awards.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Three of its series, *Arrested Development*, *Hemlock Grove* and *House of Cards*, earned a combined 14 nominations (nine for *House of Cards*, three for *Arrested Development* and two for *Hemlock Grove*).
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The *House of Cards* episode "Chapter 1" received four nominations for both the 65th Primetime Emmy Awards and 65th Primetime Creative Arts Emmy Awards, becoming the first episode of a streaming television series to receive a major Primetime Emmy Award nomination.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] With its win for Outstanding Cinematography for a Single-Camera Series, "Chapter 1" became the first episode from a streaming service to be awarded an Emmy.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] David Fincher's win for Directing for a Drama Series for *House of Cards* made the episode the first from a streaming service to win a Primetime Emmy.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] On November 6, 2013, Netflix earned its first Grammy nomination when You've Got Time by Regina Spektor—the main title theme song for *Orange Is the New Black*—was nominated for Best Song Written for Visual Media.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] On December 12, 2013, the network earned six nominations for Golden Globe Awards, including four for *House of Cards*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Among those nominations was Wright for Golden Globe Award for Best Actress – Television Series Drama for her portrayal of Claire Underwood, which she won.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] With the accolade, Wright became the first actress to win a Golden Globe for a streaming television series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] It also marked Netflix's first major acting award.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] *House of Cards* and *Orange is the New Black* also won Peabody Awards in 2013.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] On January 16, 2014, Netflix became the first streaming service to earn an Academy Award nomination when *The Square* was nominated for Best Documentary Feature.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] On July 10, 2014, Netflix received 31 Emmy nominations.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Among other nominations, *House of Cards* received nominations for Outstanding Drama Series, Outstanding Directing in a Drama Series and Outstanding Writing in a Drama Series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Kevin Spacey and Robin Wright were nominated for Outstanding Lead Actor and Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] *Orange is the New Black* was nominated in the comedy categories, earning nominations for Outstanding Comedy Series, Outstanding Writing for a Comedy Series and Outstanding Directing for a Comedy Series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Netflix got the largest share of 2016 Emmy Award nominations, with 16 major nominations.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] However, streaming shows only got 24 nominations out of a total of 139, falling significantly behind cable.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The 16 Netflix nominees were: *House of Cards* with Kevin Spacey, *A Very Murray Christmas* with Bill Murray, *Unbreakable Kimmy Schmidt*, *Master of None*, and *Bloodline*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In December 2017, Netflix was awarded PETA's Company of the Year for promoting animal rights movies and documentaries like *Forks Over Knives* and *What the Health*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] At the 90th Academy Awards, held on March 4, 2018, the film *Icarus*, distributed by Netflix, won its first Academy Award for Best Documentary Feature Film.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] During his remarks backstage, director and writer Bryan Fogel remarked that Netflix had "single-handedly changed the documentary world." *Icarus* had its premiere at the 2017 Sundance Film Festival and was bought by Netflix for $5 million, one of the biggest deals ever for a non-fiction film.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Netflix became the network whose programs received more nomination at the 2018 Primetime and Creative Arts Emmy Awards with 112 nominations, therefore breaking HBO's 17-years record as a network whose programs received more nomination at the Emmys, which received 108 nominations.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] On January 22, 2019, films distributed by Netflix scored 15 nominations for the 91st Academy Awards, including Academy Award for Best Picture for Alfonso Cuarón's *Roma*, which was nominated for 10 awards.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The 15 nominations equal the total nominations films distributed by Netflix had received in previous years.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In 2020, Netflix received 20 TV nominations and films distributed by Netflix also got 22 film nominations at the 78th Golden Globe Awards.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] It secured three out of the five nominations for best drama TV series for *The Crown*, *Ozark* and *Ratched* and four of the five nominations for best actress in a TV series: Olivia Colman, Emma Corrin, Laura Linney and Sarah Paulson.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In 2020, Netflix earned 24 Academy Award nominations, marking the first time a streaming service led all studios.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Netflix also received the most nominations of any studio at the 93rd Academy Awards—35 total nominations with 7 award wins.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In February 2022, *The Power of the Dog*, a gritty western distributed by Netflix and directed by Jane Campion, received 12 nominations, including Best Picture, for the 94th annual Academy Awards.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Films distributed by the streamer received a total of 72 nominations.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Campion became the third female to receive the Best Director award, winning her second Oscar for *The Power of the Dog*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] At the 50th International Emmy Awards, Netflix original *Sex Education* won Best Comedy Series.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Later that year, Netflix received 26 Emmy Awards including six for *Squid Game*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The *Squid Game* wins for Outstanding Lead Actor in a Drama Series and Outstanding Directing for a Drama Series were the first-ever for a non-English language series in those categories.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In March 2023, Netflix won six Academy Awards including four for *All Quiet on the Western Front* which was the most awarded Netflix film in its history.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] *Guillermo del Toro's Pinocchio* was the first streaming film to win Best Animated Feature and *The Elephant Whisperers* was the first Indian-produced film to receive Best Documentary Short Film.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In July 2024, Netflix received 107 Emmy nominations, which was the most of any network.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In January 2025, Netflix received 18 Academy Award nominations across six titles—the most of any studio.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Thirteen of those nominations belonged to the musical crime drama *Emilia Pérez,* making it the most nominated film of the year and the most nominated non-English language film in Academy history.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] *Emilia Pérez* ultimately won an award for Best Original Song for "El Mal" and Zoe Saldaña was awarded Best Supporting Actress.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In July 2025, Netflix received 120 Emmy nominations, including 13 nods for *Adolescence*, 11 for *Monsters: The Lyle and Erik Menendez Story* and 10 for *Black Mirror*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] It won 30, including eight for Outstanding Limited or Anthology Series winner *Adolescence*.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The show's star, Owen Cooper, was the youngest Emmy winner ever in any male acting category at 15 years old.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In January 2026, Netflix received 17 Academy Award nominations across six titles.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Customers of Netflix have complained about price increases in Netflix offerings dating back to the company's decision to separate its DVD rental and streaming services, which was quickly reversed.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] As Netflix increased its streaming output, it has faced calls to limit accessibility to graphic violence and include viewer advisories for issues such as sensationalism and promotion of pseudoscience.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Netflix's content has also been criticized by disability rights movement advocates for lack of closed captioning quality.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The launch of ad-supported plans has also been criticized by some subscribers as undermining Netflix's once ad-free experience.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Some media organizations and competitors have criticized Netflix for selectively releasing ratings and viewer numbers of its original programming.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The company has made claims boasting about viewership records without providing data to substantiate its successes or using problematic estimation methods.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In March 2020, some government agencies called for Netflix and other streamers to limit services due to increased broadband and energy consumption as use of the platform increased.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In response, the company announced it would reduce bit rate across all streams in Europe, thus decreasing Netflix traffic on European networks by around 25%.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] These same steps were later taken in India.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Netflix played a major role in changing how audiences watch television by encouraging binge-watching, in which viewers watch multiple episodes of a series in one sitting.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] The company’s practice of releasing entire seasons of original shows at once differed from the traditional weekly television schedule.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] Netflix also contributed to the decline of cable television by making streaming more popular and increasing demand for original online content.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In May 2022, Netflix's shareholder Imperium Irrevocable Trust filed a lawsuit against the company for violating the US securities laws.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In January 2024, a federal judge dismissed the suit, stating that shareholders failed to provide instances of Netflix lying about subscriber growth.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] In May 2023, Netflix officially banned the use of password sharing between individuals of different households, meaning sharing an account was only available to those living in the same house.
[src:metaflow/netflix-p03] After reporting a record number of new subscribers in Q4 2024, Netflix raised prices in early 2025, and again in March 2026.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow is a human-friendly Python library that makes it straightforward to develop, deploy, and operate various kinds of data-intensive applications, in particular those involving data science, ML, and AI.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow was originally developed at Netflix to boost the productivity of data scientists who work on a wide variety of projects, from classical statistics to state-of-the-art deep learning.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow is available as open-source under the Apache License, Version 2.0.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow provides a unified API to the whole infrastructure stack that is required to execute data science projects from prototype to production.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] You could use a separate tool for each of these layers but many data scientists prefer using a unified, thoughtfully designed library.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] This also minimizes the operational burden for engineers who manage the infrastructure.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Based on our experiences with hundreds of data science and ML projects, we believe that projects should grow gradually from quick experiments on the laptop, conducted by a single data scientist, to business-critical production deployments developed by a team of experts.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] In contrast to traditional software engineering, it is hard to assess the value of a DS/ML project without running realistic experiments, like backtesting models at scale, exposing a prototype to business stakeholders, or running a live A/B test.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] This should be doable without a high upfront cost.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] When the value of the project has been proven, it shouldn't be too hard to take the project all the way to large-scale production.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] **Scaling**: There is only so much data and compute you can manage on a laptop.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] It is very convenient to be able to test workflows at scale as early as possible.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] This gives you a good idea of how the system is going to behave in production, at no risk.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] **Production**: A defining feature of any production deployment is *high availability*.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] No matter how the project is deployed to production, it shouldn't require any human attention.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow supports this through production-grade workflow orchestrators, deploying to which require no changes in the code.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Also, the team needs to be able to continue development of new versions of the project alongside any production deployments and be able to A/B test them easily.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] And, as you needs grow, you may want to start building larger, reactive systems using individual flows as building blocks.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] You can assess the value of the project at every stage before deciding to invest more.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] A core tenet of Metaflow is to make simple things simple and demanding production-deployments possible.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Read more about the journey from prototype to production in Introduction to Developing with Metaflow.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Also - don't consider only the happy path!
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Any real-world project should account for failures, consider how the system is monitored, and provide clear playbooks for debugging issues occurring at any point in the project's lifecycle, production issues in particular.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] You can get started with local development by `pip` installing Metaflow like any other Python library.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] To benefit from scaling and production features of Metaflow, you need to deploy Metaflow to your cloud account or Kubernetes cluster which can be done using our Terraform or Cloudformation templates which shouldn't take more than 15-30 minutes, unless you want to customize the setup.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Take a look at an overview of Metaflow infrastructure for more information.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] In general, engineering teams like Metaflow as it integrates well with the company's existing infrastructure instead of introducing major new components.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow works with all the major cloud providers: AWS, Azure, and GCP.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] It provides native, thoroughly-tested integrations to popular systems like AWS Batch, AWS Step Functions, Kubernetes, Argo Workflows, and Apache Airflow.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Many teams find it comforting to know that Metaflow has been used for serious, large-scale production use cases involving tens of thousands of flows and millions of runs for more than four years, so the codebase is extremely well tested and battle-hardened.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Also, we provide a strong guarantee of backwards compatibility for the user-facing API, so you get to stand on a solid foundation.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] **Criticality**: Is it important that results are produced correctly and in a timely manner?
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] **Complexity**: Does the project have many moving pieces or many people working together?
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] If you answered "yes" to any of the above, keep on reading - Metaflow can help you!
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] If the answer is "no" to all of the above, Metaflow doesn't provide much benefit.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] This is a valid scenario, for instance, when you are hacking small-scale experiments in a notebook.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] You should come back when the project is ready to move to the next stage.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] When the time is right, moving from notebooks-only to notebooks-with-Metaflow should be a smooth sailing.
[src:metaflow/what-is-metaflow] Metaflow is designed to be user-friendly and welcoming to all data scientists and ML/AI engineers, novice and experts alike, who want to start building end-to-end applications independently.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] A **workflow engine** is a software application that manages business processes.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] It is a key component in workflow technology and typically makes use of a database server.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] A workflow engine manages and monitors the state of activities in a workflow, such as the processing and approval of a loan application form, and determines which new activity to transition to according to defined processes (workflows).
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] The actions may be anything from saving an application form in a document management system to sending a reminder e-mail to users or escalating overdue items to management.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] A workflow engine facilitates the flow of information, tasks, and events.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] Workflow engines may also be referred to as Workflow Orchestration Engines.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] A workflow engine is a core technique for task allocation software, such as business process management, in which the workflow engine allocates tasks to different executors while communicating data among participants.
[src:metaflow/workflow-engine] A workflow engine can execute any arbitrary sequence of steps, for example, a healthcare data analysis.
